HOUSE RESOLUTION 146
By Lamberth
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Paul Trowbridge
Gillespie, Jr., of Memphis.
WHEREAS, the members of this legislative body were greatly saddened to learn of the
passing of Paul Trowbridge Gillespie, Jr., the father of our valued colleague Representative
John Gillespie; and
WHEREAS, Paul Trowbridge Gillespie, Jr., was an exemplary public servant and
consummate professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow
citizens in numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on June 6, 1947, in Morristown, New Jersey, Mr. Gillespie was the son
of the late Paul Trowbridge Gillespie and Dorothy Anderson Gillespie; and
WHEREAS, Paul Gillespie moved to Memphis at a young age and attended
Presbyterian Day School and then Memphis University School, where he excelled as a member
of both the football and basketball teams; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Gillespie continued his athletic career and played for legendary
Memphis University School coaches Jake Rudolph and Jerry Peters; he earned a football
scholarship to Vanderbilt University and played on the 1965 freshmen team before starting as a
defensive back; and
WHEREAS, following his graduation from Vanderbilt, Paul Gillespie returned to Memphis
and began his career at First Tennessee Investment Management, while concurrently serving
as a member of the Army National Guard; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Gillespie cofounded Southeastern Asset Management in 1975; in 1985,
he went on to cofound NewSouth Capital Management, where he fostered connections with
colleagues and clients alike for forty years; and
HR0146
012105
- 1 -

WHEREAS, a highly respected member of his community, Mr. Gillespie served as
chairman for a number of boards, including Memphis University School, ArtsMemphis, Baptist
Memorial Health Care Corporation Community Advisory Board, and the Trezevant Manor
Foundation; additionally, he was president of the Liberty Bowl in 1986 and served on the
selection committee for a number of years; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Gillespie was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Paul Gillespie will be sadly missed yet fondly remembered by his beloved
wife of forty-seven years, Elizabeth Johnston Gillespie; his sons, Paul Trowbridge (Paige)
Gillespie III, Stuart Johnston (Alexis) Gillespie, and John Marston Gillespie (fiancée Mackenzie);
his grandchildren, Bailey Elizabeth Gillespie, Paul Trowbridge Gillespie IV, and Grace Hastings
Gillespie; his sister, Grace "Gaye" Gillespie (Haywood) Henderson; and nine nieces and
nephews, whom he loved dearly; and
WHEREAS, Paul Gillespie was a lifelong member of St. John's Episcopal Church, which
he served as senior warden on the vestry, helped lead the campaign to build the Parish Life
Center, and contributed to numerous stewardship efforts; and
WHEREAS, the epitome of diligence and joy, Mr. Gillespie was proud to live a life of
service and always endeavored to leave a positive impact on the community he so ably served
and cherished for nearly eighty years; and
WHEREAS, Paul Gillespie leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this legislative body should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
- 2 - 012105

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor the
memory of Paul Trowbridge Gillespie, Jr., reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and
his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Gillespie.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
